since join their very affordable monthly subscription , i 've find ticktick to be an indispensable part in my daily routine , and it be actually help i be more productive even though i be a pretty begrudge procrastinator . first off , the widget . god , i love the widget ! the first thing i see after unlock my phone be a ) a list of all the stuff i need to be do on that give day ; and b ) a cute visual checklist of daily habit that i need to also make time for . this be what i find be miss back when i use the todoist app , be a simple mean of have both habit and to - do live in the same shared ecosystem . i suppose there be technically more dedicated habit app with deep tracking feature , but what be here be perfectly functional , and easily integrate into your regular ' inbox'/'today ' list . the widget update dynamically , right along with the full - screen app , and also with the pc and web integration . this be a " must - have " feature , because i 've try other productivity app where there be lag time between input on the widget , and see they " refresh " into existence several minute later in the app itself . ticktick make everything instant , to the point that a ticktick notification ' ping ' on my phone at the precise moment it also ' ping ' on my laptop . i really can not understate how useful the widget and cross - platform integration be , because for someone like i who procrastinate a lot and forget what i be mean to be do at any random moment , it be so useful to just open up my phone and instantly have my most important task / habit slap i in the face , demand my attention . this also tie in nicely with the way notification / alert work . i 've get reminder set on all my habit , and when the reminder go off , they actually " take over " the entire screen , at which point i can tick they off , or dig into the more extensive option on the back - end . there be a few area i can see for quality - of - life improvement , though i be optimistic that their subscription model mean we have not see the " final " iteration of this app for some time yet . a few thing that jump out at i over a couple month ' usage : -- to mark a habit as " incomplete " , you can not just double - tap the checkbox for an ' x ' mark , you have to open the app , pull up the relevant habit in the dashboard , go into its setting , and the option be bury all the way in the app 's back - end menu . it be a minor gripe , but when compound over week or month of use , it be easy to just not bother mark your " failure " at all . it make i wonder if there be other useful feature i 've miss just because they be not readily accessible on the front end ui + widget . -- it would be nice if habit display in the widget + front - end ui have a visual indicator of how many day that habit have be on " streak " for . you can track those metric , but again it be hide in the robust - yet - opaque back - end , accessible via sub - menus and abstract graph , rather than be loudly display front - and - centre . i would probably be more motivated to " keep the streak go " with a give habit if i could see at a split - second glance how today 's effort fit into the context of the previous 7 day , or whatever . --also , you can set habit to only repeat on certain day of the week , or a certain number of time per week , but again its not really visible at a quick glance to know if you be on track or fall behind . by which i mean , when i pull up my habit for thursdayy , for instance , and i see " exercise at gym " in my list of habit for that day , then surely i should get some indication of " you 've be to the gym x time this week so far , and you have y gym session remain for this week [ in order to fulfil your habitual obligation ] " . again , the information be there in the app , but you have to actively seek it out . maybe the more fastidious time - keeper will see to this without bat an eye , but for forgetful , adhd - prone type like myself , if it be not right in front of i then it might as well not exist . but all in all , these be minor foible . fantastic app . 5/5 .
